ladders.explanation:
This full problem requires implementing linear search from scratch and comparing it to binary search. The intuition is that linear search works by sequentially checking each element until the target is found or the array ends, making it universally applicable but inefficient for large datasets. The algorithm: 1) Accept array and target as input. 2) Initialize index variable to -1 (not found). 3) Loop through each element from first to last. 4) Compare current element with target. 5) If match found, store index and break. 6) Return index. Time complexity is O(n) as we may examine all n elements in worst case. Space complexity is O(1) using only constant extra variables. This connects to the broader problem by demonstrating the brute-force approach that binary search improves upon. Common mistakes include: forgetting to handle empty arrays (should return -1), not breaking early when found (wastes time), and off-by-one errors in loop bounds. The linear search pattern is fundamental to many algorithms and serves as baseline for understanding more efficient searches.

Pseudocode:
function linear_search(arr, target):
    for i from 0 to len(arr)-1:
        if arr[i] == target:
            return i
    return -1

This sub-routine focuses on the iterative comparison process that forms the heart of linear search. The intuition is that to find an element in an unordered collection, we must examine elements one by one until we either find a match or exhaust all possibilities. The algorithm: 1) Receive array and target as parameters. 2) Set up a loop counter from 0 to array length minus 1. 3) In each iteration, access the current element using the index. 4) Compare the element's value with the target value. 5) If equal, we've found our target and can terminate early. 6) If loop completes without finding match, target doesn't exist in array. Time complexity is O(n) where n is array length, as we may need to check every element. Space complexity is O(1) using only the loop variable. This feeds into the full linear search by providing the actual search mechanism—the full problem adds input validation and return value handling. Common mistakes include: using wrong comparison operator (== vs =), not handling array bounds correctly, and forgetting that array indices start at 0. This pattern appears in many algorithms where sequential processing is required.

Pseudocode:
function compare_loop(arr, target):
    for i in range(len(arr)):
        if arr[i] == target:
            return True  # Found
    return False  # Not found

This core logic demonstrates the fundamental pattern of checking elements in sequence while allowing early termination when the target is found. The intuition is that in an unsorted array, we have no information about where the target might be, so we must check positions systematically. However, once we find the target, further checking is unnecessary—this early exit optimization distinguishes linear search from simply scanning the entire array. The algorithm: 1) Start at the first element (index 0). 2) Check if current element equals target. 3) If yes, stop immediately and report success. 4) If no, move to next element. 5) Repeat until either found or end of array reached. Time complexity ranges from O(1) (if target is first element) to O(n) (if target is last or not present). Space complexity is O(1). This connects to the comparison loop by adding the crucial optimization of early exit—without this, we'd waste time checking remaining elements after finding the target. Common mistakes include: continuing to check after finding the target (inefficient), not considering that the target might appear multiple times (we only need first occurrence), and confusing this with complete array traversal algorithms. This pattern is essential for understanding why linear search can sometimes be fast but is unreliable for large datasets.

Pseudocode:
function sequential_check(arr, target):
    i = 0
    while i < len(arr):
        if arr[i] == target:
            break  # Early exit when found
        i = i + 1
    if i < len(arr):
        return i  # Found at position i
    else:
        return -1  # Not found
